@node intro "What is this strange named program?"
This program is a public screen program.  What it does is open up a
public screen, upon which any other program which has the option of
starting up on a public screen will be able to use this screen.
@endnode

@node requirements "What's needed for this amazing program?"
This program requires:
    - an Amiga (:-))
    - Kickstart/WB 2.0+
    - reqtools.library v38 or higher (not included)

You should already have reqtools.library in your system, as it's
available readily from many other sources.
@endnode

@node usage "How to use this stupendous program."
Well, you can start it from the CLI or Workbench.  From the CLI, the only
command line argument it takes is a "?".  So, starting it with "pubby ?"
will produce a short description of the program, along with the current
version number, etc.  Typing "pubby" alone will start the program.

From the Workbench, it takes no tooltypes.  Just double click on the
very poorly drawn icon, and you're away.

When it's started, a reqtools screenmode requester will pop up allowing
you to select any screenmode you desire, including overscan, autoscroll,
width and height, colors, etc.  You can even open up a HAM or EHB screen.
I don't know what use these types of screens will be to anyone, but I
included them because perhaps someone out there can make use of it.

If you want to allow the shell to close after it's been runned,
type "run >nil: pubby".  With this, you can put it in your user-startup.

After you select OK, the screen will be opened, with the screen name
(and the name of program) in the title bar.  There is one menu, with two
menu items.  One is "About..." which pops up a requester advertising
myself. :-)

The other menu item says "Quit", and if you haven't yet guessed, it
will close down the screen and quit the program.

There is one condition with selecting Quit: you must send me $60, or
it won't quit. :-)  (Just kidding.)  If there are any windows on
the Pubby screen, Pubby will not quit until the last window is closed,
at which time it will immediately quit after the window is closed.

If you try to run the program when another copy of Pubby is already
running, one of two things will happen, depending on how you started
it.  If you started it from the CLI, you'll get a message back telling
you there is a version of Pubby already running.  If you started it
from the Workbench, nothing will happen, it just won't run.

You can drop it into your WBStartup drawer if you want too.

Also, the program can be made resident (that is, it can be if I remember
to set the appropriate flag when compiling.  I'll try and remember.)
If, when you get the file, you want it to resident, and the pure
bit is not set, set it, then you can make it resident.  (Gee, I hope
I got that right.  I sometimes get confused with pure, and resident
and re-entrant and stuff like that.)
Right now, this is not much use though.
@endnode

@node bugs "Is this perfect or what?"
As far as I know, there are no bugs.  I just fixed the memory bug,
so it's no longer present.

BTW, when testing it, I was trying to open up Amigaguide
on it, but it wouldn't do it.  When I tried specifying a public
screen for Amigaguide to open on, it kept telling me it couldn't
open the database (even though I was also specifying a database).
I also tried opening it up on other Public screens, but to no
avail.  I assume this is a bug with Amigaguide.

If you find any bugs, please let @{"me" link author} so I can
repair it.
@endnode

@node future "Is my beloved proggie going to survive the Armageddon?"
Well, supposedly, there's supposed to be some massive natural disasters
near then end of this century, with California dropping into the ocean,
the Great Lakes emptying into the Gulf of Mexico, and most of Ireland
being claimed by the sea.

How does Pubby fair in all this?  Well, keep your Amiga dry and
everything should be great for Pubby's future.

OK, let's screw my head back on a little bit and be serious.
Here are some of my future aspirations for Pubby:
- Find the memory bug :-)  (Found!!  See @{"history" link history} section)
- Allow multiple copies, with names like Pubby.1, Pubby.2, etc.
- Definitely, I'm going to allow user-specified screen names.
- Another definitely is to allow the user to specify any screenmode
  in a config file, or via command line arguments, so one doesn't have
  to go through the startup requester.  Right now, this makes Pubby
  kind of impractical to be put in user-startup (but it's not
  that bad.)
- Thought about making adding a preferences window with gadgets and
  stuff, but that would make Pubby quite a bit bigger.  Unsure about
  this at the moment.
- Making it a commodity, so it can be controlled by Exchange (unsure about
  this part as well.)

If you have any other enhancements or suggestions, you can e-mail me,
the @{"author" link author}.
@endnode


@node legal "Here's all the legal stuff."
This program is freeware, I guess.  (Perhaps I should just make it
public domain...naw!)  You can use it, recompile it, fix it, sleep
with it, or do whatever you want with it, as long as it has nothing
to do with a commercial product/company.  If so, e-mail @{"me" link author}, just to let
me know, and I will let you use it, but I want to try and kiss-up so I
can get a free product from you.  Also, you can't sell it for a profit, but
only for a small fee for the disk (say $5 max.)

Also, if you change/fix/add something, feel free to release it
but I'd like to be notified, or better yet, e-mailed a copy of the new
program.

I accept no responsibility for anything, including this program.
If you run this program, and your computer starts swearing
at you, starts spouting green snot, or tells you your dead
great-great grandfather is calling, or anything else, it's
not my fault.

(Now, wasn't that funny?? :-)  Or do I need to work on
my humor a little. :-)

LATE EDITION NEWSCAST:  I was just robbed!  Last night sometime, when
I was sleeping, someone broke into my car and stole my speakers and a
case of tapes.  On top of that, they wrecked my trunk keyhole (looks like
they took a screwdriver to it or something to get in).

To help overcome this injustice, everyone who reads this must send me
$100, so I can go out and purchase a new set of speakers!!!!

(Of course, you don't have to. :-)
@endnode

@node author "I'm very important."
Now, about me.  My name is Todd Courtnage, and I'm a nerd.  I don't
wear glasses, but I'm still a nerd.

At present, I'm in my last semester at the University of Regina, majoring
in Computer Science.  I hope I can find a job when I get out, if not I'll
have to make some arrangements at the Bank of Mom&Dad and/or take up
residences at La Parents Hotel. :-)

This is my second Amiga C program, my first was a game called
Totally Useless Game, and is available on finer Aminet sites everywhere.
(It's in the game/role directory, with a filename of TUG.lha (I think)).
It's a text adventure with a very unique twist.  It's played straight
from the shell, and the idea is to escape out of a house that you're
trapped in.  There was one reason I wrote it.  To put DICE through it's
paces before I registered.  DICE passed, so I registered (and one
can't beat the $50 registration!)  I also wanted to make TUG funny.
I think I succeeded, but then I have a weird sense of humor.

At present, you can reach me via a number of ways:
