@endnode

@node source "This is the finest piece of code you'll every see (probably)."
I've included the source code for two reasons.
1) Hopefully some more experienced coders can point out problems, suggestions,
   and improvements.
2) The comments.  I feel I commented my code in such a way that beginner
   programmers can make some use of it to help them out.

Now, the more lengthy discussion.  I commented my code very heavily.
I feel that this commenting can be helpful to some people.  This
doesn't mean the code is very good, it's not, but the comments, I
think, help understand the ideas and thoughts behind the code, so
it can be very helpful.  Most code I've seen is kind of useless,
because the comments are short and unhelpful for anyone other than
the most experienced.  Hopefully my code isn't like this.

Also, in some comments, I have posed questions that I don't
understand.  I put them in there, so someone in the know can help explain
things to me.  One example is when looking for a "?" as a command line
argument, and using "argv[1][0]=='?'" to check to see if it's a ?.  It
doesn't make sense to me, because the above implies that argv is a
two-dimensional array, but it's not, but trying to use argv[1]=='?'
doesn't work.  Anyway, this is one of the questions I've posed
in my comments.

Compiling:
If you wish to compile this with DICE, use:
dcc pubby.c -o pubby -l reqtoolss.lib
Naturally, you need the complete ReqTools archive with the source
code and headers and link libraries and have it all setup.
I have explained why I have to compile with -l reqtoolss.lib flag
in the comments (and it took me a LONG time to figure this out!)

Since DICE automatically opens up system libraries, I'm not opening
up intuition.library or gadtools.library.  I don't know how GCC or
SAS/C handles this, so some changes may have to be made to get it
to compile with these and others I might not have heard of.

If you do something with the code (i.e. fix it up, add to it, etc),
please e-mail me a copy of the new code, or at least e-mail me indicating
what you did, so I can keep an eye out for it.
@endnode

@node history "What's been done recently"
v1.0    Initial release (what were you expecting?  :-)

v1.01   Bug fix - found the memory bug.  After opening up the screenmode
                  requester, I wasn't freeing the requester structure, and
                  that was eating 112 bytes of memory each time the program
                  was run.  I've documented it in the source file.
        Also, with this release, I've documented the fact that Pubby can be
        made resident, although it's not of too much use right now.

@endnode

